[1] South Korea, 7 new cases - MOH 14 Jun 2015
Date: Sun 14 Jun 2015
Source: South Korean Ministry of Health [in Korean, trans. by Korean subscribers, edited]
http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=323394


7 additional MERS cases, a total of 145
--------------------------
- The Ministry of Health and Welfare's MERS-CoV Task Force as of 14 Jun 2015, has confirmed 7 additional positive cases of MERS-CoV (cases were confirmed on 13 Jun 2015).

- 4 diagnosed cases have been in contact with case no.14, 3 of them are suspected to be infected at the Samsung Medical Center Emergency Room (27-29 May 2015), and 1 case is suspected to have accompanied one of the outpatients (27 May 2015).

- For the rest 3 diagnosed cases, one has been in contact with case no.16 (25-28 May 2015) the Dae Cheong Hospital; other has been in contact with case no.15 who resided on the same floor at the Hallym University Medical Center (27-28 May 2015), and the last case who accompanied the case no.76 during the ambulance transportation (4- 6 Jun 2015).

- Remaining 5 cases are related cases at Samsung Medical Center and are currently under epidemiological investigation.

- Therefore, until now, there has been a total of 145 confirmed-cases of MERS-CoV, 10 cases have recovered and have been discharged from the hospital, 14 cases of deaths and 121 cases are receiving treatment.

- On the other hand, for the 5 cases presented on 13 Jun 2015 (having been confirmed on 12 Jun 2015), all 5 cases were all confirmed to have stayed at the Samsung Medical Center emergency room with case no.14 (27-29 May 2015).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[With the reports of 7 additional cases, there have now been a total of 145 laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection in South Korea (counting the one case that was ultimately confirmed by China as he traveled there while ill). This includes 14 fatalities and 10 recoveries discharged from the hospitals.

Of the recently confirmed cases, 6 were 3rd generation cases having been in health facilities where 2nd generation cases were being treated and one was a 4th generation case, having accompanied a 3rd generation case to the hospital in an ambulance.

Information on the 5 cases reported on 13 Jun 2015 that were still under investigation at the time of the report, all 5 cases were 3rd generation cases having been in the emergency room at Samsung Hospital when case no.14 was there. Of note is that 71 (49.0 percent) of the confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection were associated with contact with case no.14.

There have now been 3 4th generation cases reported.

The HealthMap/ProMED map of South Korea can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3435317,195 and a map of South Korea showing provinces can be found at http://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/korea-south-administrative-map.htm.]

