[5] Media tidbits, global reactions
Date: Sat 13 Jun 2015


Hong Kong
"There is a general sense of fear in Hong Kong after news broke on Wednesday [10 Jun 2015] that a woman suspected of having Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS) had been rushed to Princess Margaret Hospital for testing. The woman, who had sought treatment at a clinic in Tsing Yi MTR Station, had returned from Seoul and showed signs of fever and a running nose."
http://news.asiaone.com/news/asia/mers-fears-loom-over-dead-town
[Hong Kong has not forgotten SARS.... - Mod.MPP]

Philippines
"Another Filipino has been infected with the Middle East respiratory syndrome-coronavirus (MERS-CoV) in Saudi Arabia, the Philippine embassy in Riyadh has confirmed."
http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2015/06/14/1465638/embassy-saudi-says-pinoy-has-mers-virus
[There were recent reports of expats with MERS-CoV in Saudi Arabia -- a 55-year-old male in Jeddah and a 58-year-old male in Riyadh, both reported on 5 Jun 2015. - Mod.MPP]

"The Private Hospitals Association of the Philippines Inc. (PHAPi) yesterday admitted that most private hospitals are not prepared to handle the Middle East respiratory syndrome-coronavirus (MERS-CoV) which has reached South Korea and killed 14 people there. PHAPi president Rustico Jimenez said only a few private hospitals in the Philippines are physically capable to treat MERS-CoV patients so 'we should never let the virus in.'"
http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2015/06/14/1465641/hospitals-phl-unprepared-possible-outbreak
[Reality testing.... - Mod.MPP]

Slovakia
"South Korean man thought to have contracted the potentially deadly MERS virus was hospitalised in the Slovak capital Bratislava on Saturday [13 Jun 2015], a spokeswoman said. 'He is a 38-year-old man from South Korea who is suffering from diarrhoea, fever and lesions on his skin,' Petra Stano Matasovska, from Bratislava's university hospital, told AFP."
http://www.ndtv.com/world-news/south-korean-man-thought-to-have-mers-hospitalised-in-slovakia-771419
[Fever, diarrhea and rash ... some coronavirus (both SARS and MERS) have presented with diarrhea. - Mod.MPP]

Malaysia
Sarawak (Borneo): "A woman suspected of contracting the Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) after a trip to Mecca last month [May 2015] was believed taken away from Miri Hospital by her family members on Friday night [12 Jun 2015] -- a few hours after admission."
http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/06/14/police-tracking-down-mers-suspect-who-checked-out-from-miri-hospital/
[Were specimens taken before she left? Another media report says, "The source also said the woman had just returned home from her pilgrimage in Mecca and was quarantined pending her sputum test results," and that the woman is "back in Brunei" (http://www.therakyatpost.com/news/2015/06/13/suspected-mers-cov-patient-flees-miri-hospital/). - Mod.MPP]

China
"As the number of confirmed MERS cases continues to rise in South Korea, thousands of tourists have cancelled their holidays to the country.... However, the emergence of MERS threatens to hit the tourism industry hard. The Korea Tourism Organisation said that between [1 and 9 Jun 2015], 67 700 international tourists from 30 different countries cancelled their visits to South Korea. More than 100 000 mainland Chinese were expected to have cancelled their tours to South Korea by the end of the month, Xinhua reported."
http://www.scmp.com/news/asia/article/1821231/tourists-and-their-money-skipping-south-korea-mers-crisis-persists
[Aspects of the economic impact of the outbreak. - Mod.MPP]

